In C++, explicitly declaring a destructor as `virtual` is necessary when you expect the class to be used as a base class for inheritance, as it ensures that the destructors of derived classes are called appropriately when an object is deleted through a pointer to the base class. This is essential to prevent resource leaks and to ensure proper cleanup of derived class resources.

However, if your destructor has an empty implementation, you can safely make use of the `default` keyword, which tells the compiler to generate the default implementation. This results in clearer and more concise code, and the compiler-generated destructor is typically as efficient as an empty one you would write yourself.

Here's an example with a virtual destructor:

```cpp
class Shape {
public:
    virtual ~Shape() = default; // Default virtual destructor
};

class Rect : public Shape {
    // ... other members and functions ...
};
```

Using `= default;` is a clear statement of intent that there is nothing special to be done in the destructor, while still ensuring that it remains virtual and will correctly call destructors of any derived class instances.

Defaulting the destructor is generally a good practice when your class doesn't need to manage resources like dynamically allocated memory, file handles, network connections, or other system resources that need explicit cleanup. If the destructor is already empty and virtual, changing it to be defaulted is a matter of preference and consistency in your codebase but is often seen as an improvement for code clarity.

Remember, you only need to declare a destructor as `virtual` if your class is going to be used polymorphically – that is, if you intend to delete derived class instances via base class pointers. If there's no inheritance, or no resources to manage, you may not need to declare a destructor at all; the compiler will generate a default one for you.

If you're designing classes such as `Point`, `FPoint`, `Rect`, and other shape-related classes without the intention of using them polymorphically, meaning you do not plan to inherit from them and then delete instances of derived classes through base class pointers, you do not need to declare virtual destructors.

For utility classes like `Point` that simply hold data and have no resources to manage, you typically don't need a user-declared destructor at all — the default destructor provided by the compiler is sufficient. This also holds true for classes that encapsulate shapes or graphical elements, as long as they do not manage resources outside of automatic storage (like memory allocated with `new` or system resources).

