For manager classes like `ScreenManager`, `InputManager`, `ResourceManager`, and so forth, if you're using the singleton pattern and have them implemented as static instances within the class itself, you might not need destructors at all, depending on how you manage lifetime and resources.

Here's how a singleton pattern commonly looks in C++:

```cpp
