Yes, in C++, you can make a class abstract by declaring at least one pure virtual function. An abstract class cannot be instantiated directly, which is similar to abstract classes in C#. A pure virtual function is a virtual function that is declared by assigning the value of `0` to it in the class definition.

In your `GameScreen` class, you might want to force subclasses to provide their own implementations of certain functions. Here's how you can modify your class to be abstract:

```cpp
