{
    public:
        GameScreen();
        virtual ~GameScreen() = default;

        // You can make LoadMedia pure virtual if subclasses should provide their own implementations.
        virtual bool LoadMedia(SDL_Renderer* renderer) = 0;

        // Same for other methods that subclasses must implement
        virtual void FreeMedia() = 0;
        virtual void Draw(SDL_Renderer* renderer) = 0;
        virtual void Update(const SDL_Event& e) = 0;
};
```

By declaring these methods as pure virtual (with `= 0`), you make it clear that `GameScreen` cannot be used on its own and must be subclassed. Subclasses must provide definitions for all pure virtual functions unless they too intend to be abstract classes.

By marking the destructor as virtual and default (`virtual ~GameScreen() = default;`), you ensure that the correct destructor will be called for derived classes, while also communicating that `GameScreen` is intended to be used as a base class.

Here’s what needs to be considered when deciding which functions to make pure virtual:

1. If a function is fundamental to the operation of the subclass and doesn't make sense without a subclass-specific implementation, make it pure virtual. For example, `Draw` and `Update` might be fundamentally tied to how each specific game screen behaves.

2. If a function provides optional behavior or has some form of default implementation that may suffice for some subclasses, you might not want to make it pure virtual and instead provide a default implementation in the base class.

3. Make sure the destructors of abstract classes are declared virtual so that derived class destructors are called when a polymorphic object is deleted. The destructor should not be pure virtual (`virtual ~GameScreen() = 0;` is not correct), but it can be defaulted to indicate it doesn't do anything special.

Finally, remember to provide clear documentation for the class, explaining what functions are pure virtual and must be overridden, as well as any other responsibilities that a subclass must uphold. This makes it easier for other developers to understand how to extend your class correctly.

